Three browser commands call `Page.enable` inside a `withDebugger` callback without calling `Page.disable` before returning:

1. `platform/browser-extension/src/browser-commands/resource-commands.ts` line 110 â€” `handleBrowserListResources`
2. `platform/browser-extension/src/browser-commands/resource-commands.ts` line 157 â€” `handleBrowserGetResourceContent`
3. `platform/browser-extension/src/browser-commands/interaction-commands.ts` line 367 â€” `handleBrowserHandleDialog`

`withDebugger` (resource-commands.ts:75-98) checks `isCapturing(tabId)` to determine if a network capture session is already active. When `alreadyAttached=true`, the `finally` block skips `chrome.debugger.detach` â€” so the Page domain remains enabled on the shared capture session. This causes Chrome to send spurious Page.* CDP events (domContentEventFired, loadEventFired, frameNavigated, etc.) through the `chrome.debugger.onEvent` listener in network-capture.ts, which only handles Network.* events and silently drops them. The fix is to add `Page.disable` after the Page domain work completes.

The cleanest approach is to add a try/finally inside each withDebugger callback:
```
await withDebugger(tabId, async () => {
  await chrome.debugger.sendCommand({ tabId }, 'Page.enable');
  try {
    // ... existing logic ...
  } finally {
    await chrome.debugger.sendCommand({ tabId }, 'Page.disable').catch(() => {});
  }
});
```

Page.disable should be best-effort (catch errors silently) because if the debugger detaches or the tab closes mid-operation, the disable command will fail â€” and that's fine since the Page domain is cleaned up implicitly when the session ends.

Do NOT change the withDebugger function itself â€” it is a general-purpose utility. The fix belongs in the individual command handlers that enable Page.
